  "prompt": "Which digital circuit use by data bus to pass data from memory to register?",
  "response": "In digital circuits, the data bus is used to transfer data between different components within a computer system. To move data from memory to a register, typically within a CPU, you would employ a mechanism involving several components:\n\n1. **Bus Interface Unit (BIU)**: The BIU is responsible for driving data onto the bus and managing the data flow between the CPU, memory, and other peripherals.\n\n2. **Memory Address Register (MAR)**: This register holds the memory address from which data will be read or to which data will be written.\n\n3. **Memory Data Register (MDR)** or **Memory Buffer Register (MBR)**: This register temporarily holds data read from or written to the memory. When transferring data from memory to a register, the MDR holds the data fetched from the memory location specified by the MAR.\n\n4. **Control Unit**: This unit orchestrates the process, sending the necessary control signals to read data from memory and transfer it via the data bus to the appropriate CPU register.\n\n5. **CPU Registers**: These are high-speed storage locations within the CPU where data is temporarily held for processing. The data fetched from memory can be loaded into one of these registers for operations.\n\nThe process typically involves setting up the proper address in the MAR, initiating a read on the data bus, capturing the data in the MDR, and then transferring that data to the desired CPU register. The flow of data is synchronized by the system clock and controlled through a series of control signals.",
